  reasoning: "FIRST PASS REASONING:\nWe need to generate labels, descriptions, content_type for each field. Use summary stats and frequency distribution.\n\nContent type tokens list given; we can map based on semantics.\n\nAlso need relationships array: joint, ordered, correlated. We must identify likely relationships.\n\nGiven dataset appears to be NYC 311 complaints (NYC Open Data). Fields:\n\n- Unique Key: unique identifier integer. Content type? \"uuid\" maybe or \"unknown\". But deterministic override says unique_id if cardinality equals row count. Cardinality 1,000,000 equal to row count. So we should not use \"unique_id\" because reserved; choose more specific token like \"unknown\" or maybe \"integer\"? But allowed tokens: first_name, last_name, full_name etc. None fits integer id. Use \"unknown\". Or could use \"uuid\" if it were UUID string but it's integer. I think \"unknown\".\n\n- Created Date: datetime with format mm/dd/yyyy HH:MM:SS AM/PM? Format from frequency distribution: \"01/24/2013 12:00:00 AM\" => strftime \"%m/%d/%Y %I:%M:%S %p\". So content_type: \"datetime:%m/%d/%Y %I:%M:%S %p\".\n\n- Closed Date: similar format. Also datetime.\n\n- Agency: string but values like \"NYPD\", \"HPD\" etc. Content type: maybe \"company_name\"? But it's agency. Could use \"category\". But better \"company_name\" as agencies are organizations. The allowed tokens include \"company_name\". Yes.\n\n- Agency Name: similar; could be company_name or full_name? It's a formal name of the agency. Use \"full_name\".\n\n- Complaint Type: category of complaint. Use \"category\".\n\n- Descriptor: free text description but many specific values like \"Loud Music/Party\". Could use \"lorem_sentence\"? But better \"free_text\" because descriptor is descriptive phrase. Use \"free_text\".\n\n- Location Type: category; use \"category\".\n\n- Incident Zip: zip code 5-digit numeric string. Use \"zip_code\".\n\n- Incident Address: street address. Use \"street_address\".\n\n- Street Name: street name; use \"street_name\".\n\n- Cross Street 1: cross street; also street_name.\n\n- Cross Street 2: same.\n\n- Intersection Street 1: intersection street; street_name.\n\n- Intersection Street 2: street_name.\n\n- Address Type: category of address type. Use \"category\" or maybe \"lorem_word\"? But it's categories like ADDRESS, INTERSECTION etc. So category.\n\n- City: city name; use \"city\".\n\n- Landmark: could be free text; but values are names of landmarks. Could use \"free_text\" or \"full_name\". I'll use \"full_name\".\n\n- Facility Type: category; maybe \"category\".\n\n- Status: status of complaint; category.\n\n- Due Date: datetime with format mm/dd/yyyy HH:MM:SS AM/PM? Frequency shows \"04/08/2015 10:00:58 AM\" => same as created date. So datetime format same.\n\n- Resolution Description: free text; use \"free_text\".\n\n- Resolution Action Updated Date: datetime same format.\n\n- Community Board: category (like \"12 MANHATTAN\"). Use \"category\".\n\n- BBL: Borough Block Lot numeric string 10 digits maybe. This is unique identifier for NYC block. Content type? Could be \"unknown\" but could treat as integer or string; but no specific token. Use \"unknown\". Or \"lorem_word\"? No. We'll use \"unknown\".\n\n- Borough: borough name; could use \"state_abbr\" if abbreviation, but values are full names. Use \"city\" maybe not correct. Maybe \"state_abbr\" is only abbreviations. We can use \"full_name\" or \"category\". I'll use \"category\".\n\n- X Coordinate (State Plane): integer coordinate. No specific token; unknown.\n\n- Y Coordinate: same.\n\n- Open Data Channel Type: category of channel type. Use \"category\".\n\n- Park Facility Name: name of facility, could be free text; but maybe full_name. Use \"full_name\" or \"lorem_sentence\"? I'd use \"free_text\". But better \"full_name\" as names like \"Central Park\". We'll use \"full_name\".\n\n- Park Borough: borough; category.\n\n- Vehicle Type: category of vehicle type; category.\n\n- Taxi Company Borough: borough; category.\n\n- Taxi Pick Up Location: location description; free text. Use \"full_name\"? It includes addresses etc. Might be considered free_text. Use \"free_text\".\n\n- Bridge Highway Name: name of highway; free_text? Could use \"full_name\". We'll use \"free_text\" or \"category\". But there are many names, but category may fit; but \"Bridge Highway Name\" is a specific classification of highways maybe not categories. We'll use \"lorem_sentence\"? Not appropriate. Use \"free_text\".\n\n- Bridge Highway Direction: direction like East/Long Island Bound. Could be free text. Use \"free_text\".\n\n- Road Ramp: ramp type. Category.\n\n- Bridge Highway Segment: segment description; free_text or category. Use \"free_text\".\n\n- Latitude: float coordinate. Content type: latitude.\n\n- Longitude: longitude.\n\n- Location: pair of coordinates string. Might be considered \"lorem_sentence\"? But maybe a string of coordinates. Could use \"full_name\" or \"free_text\". I'll use \"free_text\".\n\nWe must ensure tokens are from allowed list: first_name, last_name, full_name, username, password, email, phone, street_address, street_name, building_number, secondary_address, city, state, state_abbr, zip_code, country, country_code, latitude, longitude, time_zone, company_name, industry, job_title, profession, unique_id, uuid, credit_card, currency_code, isbn, ip_address, ipv6_address, mac_address, url, user_agent, file_name, file_path, mime_type, color_hex, license_plate, date, datetime, time, duration, category, lorem_word, lorem_sentence, lorem_paragraph, free_text, unknown.\n\nWe need to pick tokens accordingly. Some fields like \"Agency\" -> company_name; \"Agency Name\" -> full_name; \"Location Type\" -> category; etc.\n\nNow relationships: We can find ordered: Created Date <= Closed Date? Data suggests that closed date may be after created date. But some rows might have null or earlier? We should identify monotonic order within each row: For each complaint, closed date is later than created date. So we can create an \"ordered\" relationship with members [\"Created Date\", \"Closed Date\"]. Anchor maybe \"Created Date\". Also due date maybe between created and closed? Not necessarily; but could be before closed. But only certain fields.\n\nAlso joint: city + borough + incident zip may relate. Could propose that \"City\" + \"Borough\" + \"Incident Zip\" are jointly correlated: each zip belongs to a specific borough and city. So joint relationship among [\"City\", \"Borough\", \"Incident Zip\"] maybe? However the dataset uses Borough as separate field. We could do joint relationship for City, Borough, Incident Zip.\n\nAlso \"Latitude\" and \"Longitude\" maybe correlated but numeric coordinates; we might treat as correlated: \"Latitude\" and \"Longitude\". But correlation not monotonic. Could classify as correlated. But spec says \"correlated - numeric fields that move together\". So we can list [\"Latitude\", \"Longitude\"] as correlated. Or maybe also X Coordinate (State Plane) & Y coordinate? Those are coordinates in state plane; they correlate with latitude/longitude but might be separate relationship.\n\nAlso \"Address Type\" + \"Location Type\"? Not necessarily joint.\n\n\"Taxi Company Borough\" and \"Borough\"? They may not be same.\n\nWe can propose:\n\n- ordered: [\"Created Date\", \"Closed Date\"], anchor \"Created Date\"\n\n- joint: [\"City\", \"Borough\", \"Incident Zip\"] (makes sense)\n\n- correlated: [\"Latitude\", \"Longitude\"]\n\nAlso maybe correlated: [\"X Coordinate (State Plane)\", \"Y Coordinate (State Plane)\"].\n\nWe should not duplicate fields across relationships. So choose a set of fields.\n\nWe must ensure no field appears in more than one relationship.\n\nLet's list all fields and decide which to include in relationships:\n\nOrdered: Created Date, Closed Date.\n\nJoint: City, Borough, Incident Zip.\n\nCorrelated: Latitude, Longitude; X Coordinate (State Plane), Y Coordinate (State Plane).\n